20–1518":"1420–1518","1344–1390":"1344–1390","1344–Female":"1344–Overleden","1415":"1415","1425":"1425","1344":"1344","1420":"1420","1395":"1395","1518":"1518","1390":"1390","Saint Monance, , Fife, Scotland":"St Monans, Fife, Schotland","Otterburn, , Northumberland, England":"Otterburn, Northumberland, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Edinburgh, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Schotland"},"en":{"1390–1425":"1390–1425","1395–Female":"1395–Deceased","1420–1518":"1420–1518","1344–1390":"1344–1390","1344–Female":"1344–Deceased","1415":"1415","1425":"1425","1344":"1344","1420":"1420","1395":"1395","1518":"1518","1390":"1390","Saint Monance, , Fife, Scotland":"St Monans, Fife, Scotland","Otterburn, , Northumberland, England":"Otterburn, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","Edinburgh, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Barton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places called with Old English <i>bere</i> or <i>bær</i> ‘barley’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’, i.e. an outlying grange. Compare   Barwick  . The name is also found in Ireland, where it has been Gaelicized as <b>de Bartún</b>.","Polish (<b>Bartoń</b>); Czech and Slovak (mainly <b>Bartoň</b>): from a pet form of the personal name Polish <i>Bartłomiej</i>, Czech <i>Bartoloměj</i>, Slovak <i>Bartolomej</i>, from Latin <i>Bartholomaeus</i> (see   Bartholomew  ). This surname is also found in Germany."],"variants":[{"name":"Barwick","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Berwick or Barwick, for example in Northumberland, Norfolk, Somerset, and Yorkshire, from Old English <i>bere</i> ‘barley’ + <i>wīc</i> ‘outlying farm building’, i.e. a granary lying some distance away from the main settlement.","North German: habitational name from a place called Berwick, near Soest, in Westphalia."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Barton was born in 1390, in St Monans, Fife, Scotland, his father, Robert Barton, was 46 and his mother, Margaret de Barton, was 46. He married Agnes Turnbull in 1415, in St Monans, Fife, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1425, in his hometown, at the age of 35."},"et":{"1390–1425":"1390–1425","1395–Female":"1395–Surnud","1420–1518":"1420–1518","1344–1390":"1344–1390","1344–Female":"1344–Surnud","1415":"1415","1425":"1425","1344":"1344","1420":"1420","1395":"1395","1518":"1518","1390":"1390","Saint Monance, , Fife, Scotland":"St Monans, Fife, Scotland","Otterburn, , Northumberland, England":"Otterburn, Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Edinburgh, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Scotland"},"fi":{"1390–1425":"1390–1425","1395–Female":"1395–Kuollut","1420–1518":"1420–1518","1344–1390":"1344–1390","1344–Female":"1344–Kuollut","1415":"1415","1425":"1425","1344":"1344","1420":"1420","1395":"1395","1518":"1518","1390":"1390","Saint Monance, , Fife, Scotland":"St Monans, Fife, Scotland","Otterburn, , Northumberland, England":"Otterburn, Northumberland, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Edinburgh, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Scotland"},"fr":{"1390–1425":"1390–1425","1395–Female":"1395–Décédée","1420–1518":"1420–1518","1344